President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 2015 as National Substance Abuse Prevention Month. The proclamation acknowledges the efforts of families, friends, teachers, and community organizations in preventing substance abuse and emphasizes the role that every person can play in this effort. The Obama Administration is committed to supporting community partners in creating positive and safe environments and has taken steps to ensure that health plans include mental health and substance use disorder services. The proclamation highlights the importance of preventing substance abuse before it begins and promoting evidence-based prevention programs. It also emphasizes the need to educate children about the dangers of drug and alcohol use and encourages parents to have open conversations with their children about these risks. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to engage in programs and activities that promote comprehensive substance abuse prevention efforts within their communities.